Text.Value: You scoundrels attacked these peaceful villagers completely unprovoked! Filthy, dim-witted...
Omeluum!
The feeling is mutual, friend. I have only passing familiarity with astral travellers.
The feeling is mutual, friend. I have only passing familiarity with the surface races.
Then you've come to the right place. The hybridisation among fungi in this circle is truly unique.
Leave.
The myconids wouldn't appreciate us fighting here. I'll listen.
You were infected by an illithid tadpole? It's a miracle you're still intact!
Our kind has suffered needlessly for generations. Do you also seek peace among the myconids?
Let me see if it will answer my summons a second time.
*As Omeluum's mind pierces yours, the tadpole pulses with power.*
That's not your business.
Truly remarkable! But why come to the Underdark, where they hold so much power?
Ah... wait. You're not with that damned raiding party. Apologies.
It is my hope that my research will lead to liberation and peace for my people.
This is where I belong, but right now I can't stay.
You betray the very reason you were hatched into this plane.
They infest your head and invade your dreams, and still you would parley?
*The scholar's brow tenses. His voice spills into your skull, the spores connecting mind to mind.*
Can you tell me more about ceremorphosis?
Running this ghaik through would be a privilege. Attack.
I'd never trust a mind flayer. Attack.
Please, hold. I understand your rage against my kin.
Could I ask what you were searching for to begin with?
Do you know anything about ceremorphosis?
A common phenomenon in the Underdark, I'm afraid.
But I assure you, I stand with the Society of Brilliance, not the colonies of my people.
So it is with the myconids: they live in harmonious unity, but each has a unique personality.
Welcome back. Have you made any new discoveries?
My colleagues and I are working to improve conditions in the Underdark. This need not be such a dire, hostile place.
Sorry, Omeluum. I'd rather not.
Exactly! It's such a relief to meet another sensible mind.
Such is nature's balance: life thriving under adversity.
Blurg, proud member of the Society of Brilliance, at your service.
I see! Well, it is the central act of mind flayer reproduction.
I am trying to return to my people.
I've never heard of the Society of Brilliance.
Welcome back. Have you made any new discoveries?
It's curious to find a githyanki here. What has brought you down so deep?
It's curious to find a surface dweller here. What has brought you down so deep?
This is not a wasteland: it is a glorious ecosystem. Every civilisation here could thrive without conflict!
Understandable. We are small in number, and rarely stay in one place for long.
Hgh--nzzt. Or perhaps not. Your mind is far more complex than that of the fungi.
Were you here when the duergar attacked?
It is! This adventurer has an illithid tadpole inside her head. But she hasn't turned.
It is! This adventurer has an illithid tadpole inside his head. But he hasn't turned.
It is! This adventurer has an illithid tadpole inside their head. But they haven't turned.
I hope this is important, Blurg. My zurkhwood samples need constant attention.
*Omeluum's tentacles flutter in what appears to be the mind flayer's approximation of a smile.*
I see. I will remain here if you change your mind.
Leave.
Pardon. Sometimes my temper gets the better of me.
Such designs are part of why I've devoted myself to studying the myconids.
Forgive me. Being inquisitive is in my nature.
Yes. Absolutely.
But I've found that there is as much to learn from an individual as there is from a community.
*It feels ten times its size. Alive, awake. Almost smug.*
I've never seen a hobgoblin like you before.
Are you looking to have it extracted?
I have a friend who may be able to assist.
You must be worried sick, but have no fear.
Ah... wait. You're not with that damned raiding party. Apologies.
The duergar are back! Run, little mushrooms!
Ah, a visitor! You're a welcome sight.
Open your mind to me. Let us see what lurks within.
You'll die choking on your own bile, ghaik!
A collective quest to eliminate the gith and enslave all other humanoids.
We all have our unique interests. Mind flayers are mine.
If that settles matters for the time being... would you like a diagnosis?
Honestly? I kind of got lost down here.
Swallow your disgust and permit the ghaik's search.
Traitor.
Fool.
You may have trouble reaching the Astral Plane from here, young gith.
Stifle your revulsion and listen to the mind flayer.
I ask only that you refrain from violence. I respect that your opinion of my kind may be... charged.
How could a ghaik be anyone's ally?
An illithid is your friend? How is that possible?
I'm not refraining from anything. You'll die like the rest.
What is the Grand Design?
A mind flayer infected me with a tadpole.
I collect mushrooms to sell on the surface.
What have your studies uncovered?
Research in the Underdark sounds like a dangerous prospect.
Relax and let Omeluum's mind search your own.
Ah, the mushroom hunter! Have you made any new discoveries?
Tell Blurg about the tadpole.
A fascinating process, if a touch grim.
And yet, we are all in need. Imagine what creativity would bloom if no craftsman starved. If every wizard had spell materials!
Ah, a visitor! You're a welcome sight.
Your kind tend to be slaves down here.
I observed the fight from a distance. Combat is not my field of expertise, but the myconids handled themselves well enough.
Ghaik. Your head will make a fine trophy for my queen!
One of my brethren forced a tadpole into your eye. Or ear, perhaps?
A ghaik! Die.
A mind flayer?! Die.
I've made a lot of strange allies for information. Let's hear it.
I have broken free from the elder brain's yoke. I no longer serve the Grand Design.
I do enjoy a good bargain, if anything in my private collection is to your liking.
But let us observe the customs of the locals.
It's true that many of my brethren are enslaved here, but my intellect has secured my freedom.
I know the feeling well. What has driven you from home?
A fascinating topic. May I ask the reason for your interest?
I'd never trust a mind flayer. Attack.
Explain the whole story.
Our peoples aren't exactly inclined to share with each other.
A tadpole is inserted into a living humanoid, and in seven days, the host is consumed to produce a new illithid.
My species has terrorised the Underdark for countless generations.
My species devastated and enslaved yours. It is unforgivable.
I want nothing to do with you.
Do you have anything interesting to trade?
Excellent! Omeluum will be happy to answer all of your questions.
I have felt the shame of Lolth herself. I understand, Omeluum.
I know what it's like to be shunned. I understand, Omeluum.
Seems like you've had a run-in with my people before.
This is pointless.
I ask that you refrain from violence, while I respect that your opinion of my kind may not change.
I... see. A fine way to make a living.

EditorData.NodeContext: Brugh looks the player up and down, clearly skeptical.

Text.Value: *There is rare magic in the Underdark too. Faerzress. It radiates from the earth, warping teleportation and divination magic.*
Never mind. I'm done with mind flayers touching me.
Can I talk to Omeluum again?
Why do you not seek refuge among your own on the surface?
Yes, but it has abundant natural resources. Spores, waterorbs, trillimac! I've studied them for years.
I must complete this study. Entertain yourself elsewhere.
Very well. I have mushrooms to catalogue.
No ceremorphosis? That's impossible! But intriguing.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Omelum] Construction animation walk to stop / Then the VO.

Synopsis: The player meets Blurg, a hobgoblin (deep orc) member of the Society of Brilliance, a group of intelligent, neutral monsters working to improve the Underdark. He talks about his research and, if the tadpole is mentioned, brings his mind flayer friend Omeluum to talk to the player. The player can either agree to the mind flayer's help or attack.
